SIMPLE: harrow
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harrow
<hw>Har"row</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧r"r⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>harowe</ets>, <ets>harwe</ets>, AS. <ets>hearge</ets>; cf. D.
<ets>hark</ets> rake, G. <ets>harke</ets>, Icel. <ets>herfi</ets>
harrow, Dan. <ets>harve</ets>, Sw. <ets>harf</ets>. ⟦root⟧16.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An implement of agriculture, usually formed of pieces
of timber or metal crossing each other, and set with iron or wooden
teeth. It is drawn over plowed land to level it and break the clods, to
stir the soil and make it fine, or to cover seed when sown.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An obstacle formed by turning an
ordinary harrow upside down, the frame being buried.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bush harrow</b></col>, <cd>a kind of light harrow made of
bushes, for harrowing grass lands and covering seeds, or to finish the
work of a toothed harrow.</cd> -- <col><b>Drill harrow</b></col>.
<cd>See under 6th <er>Drill</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Under the
harrow</b></col>, <cd>subjected to actual torture with a toothed
instrument, or to great affliction or oppression.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harrow
<hw>Har"row</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Harrowed</conjf> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧r"r⟦osl⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Harrowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>harowen</ets>, <ets>harwen</ets>; cf. Dan. <ets>harve</ets>. See
<er>Harrow</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw a harrow
over, as for the purpose of breaking clods and leveling the surface, or
for covering seed; <as>as, to <ex>harrow</ex> land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will he <qex>harrow</qex> the valleys after thee?</q> <rj><qau>Job
xxxix. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To break or tear, as with a harrow; to wound; to
lacerate; to torment or distress; to vex.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My aged muscles <qex>harrowed</qex> up with whips.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could a tale unfold, whose lightest word⟦br⟧
Would <qex>harrow</qex> up thy soul.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Harrow
<hw>Har"row</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>harau</ets>,
<ets>haro</ets>; fr. OHG. <ets>hara</ets>, <ets>hera</ets>,
<ets>herot</ets>, or fr. OS. <ets>herod</ets> hither, akin to E.
<ets>here</ets>.]</ety> <def>Help! Halloo! An exclamation of distress; a
call for succor; -- the ancient Norman hue and cry.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Harrow</xex> and well away!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Harrow</qex>! alas! here lies my fellow slain.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Harrow
<hw>Har"row</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Harry</er>.]</ety>
<def>To pillage; to harry; to oppress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Meaning thereby to <qex>harrow</qex> his people.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harrower</ent>⟦br⟧
